WEBVTT

00:08.399 --> 00:11.620
I don't know.
I feel like...

00:11.663 --> 00:14.492
I feel like these shoes are
at a different party.

00:14.536 --> 00:17.800
You know?
One where fun goes to die.

00:17.843 --> 00:20.020
So less corporate,
more red carpet?

00:20.063 --> 00:21.499
I think so. Great.

00:21.543 --> 00:23.110
Thanks, Roxanne.

00:23.153 --> 00:25.112
I really appreciate
you jumping in.

00:25.155 --> 00:27.462
Ali usually helps me
with big events,

00:27.505 --> 00:30.726
but she's doing
an internship abroad and...

00:30.769 --> 00:32.467
No problem. Okay.

00:33.511 --> 00:35.948
These should put the fun
in fundraiser.

00:35.992 --> 00:37.689
Oh, yeah. See?

00:37.733 --> 00:39.822
Now, look.

00:39.865 --> 00:42.042
This is why women
have a thing about shoes.

00:42.085 --> 00:44.087
They do?

00:44.131 --> 00:45.567
Well, that's news to me.

00:45.610 --> 00:47.047
Oh, hey, handsome.

00:47.090 --> 00:48.700
I love you in that old thing.

00:48.744 --> 00:50.920
It never gets old. That's
why it's a classic.

00:50.963 --> 00:53.923
It certainly is. Okay, I got to go over
and work on my remarks.

00:53.966 --> 00:55.055
No, d-don't touch.

00:55.098 --> 00:57.796
All right.
Good seeing you, Roxanne.

00:57.840 --> 01:00.843
Well, I think we got a winner.
What do you think?

01:00.886 --> 01:01.974
Yeah.

01:02.018 --> 01:03.846
There's just one
other wardrobe issue

01:03.889 --> 01:05.194
we should discuss
moving forward.

01:05.239 --> 01:07.197
It's about your husband.

01:07.241 --> 01:10.418
So you'll at least want to get a
drive-by with Senator Wagner.

01:10.461 --> 01:12.942
He has a sweet tooth, so
target the dessert table.

01:12.985 --> 01:15.007
And, uh, Senator Langston might
be a little harder to pin down.

01:15.031 --> 01:16.989
Oh, Sydney and
Louise Winters's winery

01:17.033 --> 01:18.967
had a great harvest coming off
an award-winning year,

01:18.991 --> 01:20.732
so you can lean on them
to up their grant.

01:20.776 --> 01:22.125
Just for one night,

01:22.169 --> 01:26.477
can we not think about
fundraising or votes?

01:26.521 --> 01:30.742
Come on. This event actually
has the potential to be fun.

01:30.786 --> 01:32.657
You might be
in the wrong profession, ma'am.

01:32.701 --> 01:34.983
I said "one night," Blake. I'm
not having a vocational crisis.

01:35.007 --> 01:37.009
Good to know. But this is Henry's
night to shine,

01:37.053 --> 01:41.797
so I am perfectly justified
staying out of the spotlight.

01:41.840 --> 01:44.234
Yes, ma'am.

01:44.278 --> 01:48.586
Oh, it's the McCords,
in glamorous formal wear.

01:48.630 --> 01:49.979
I feel itchy. Oh, youfeel itchy?

01:50.022 --> 01:52.895
Well, y-you look really g...
That looks great.

01:53.939 --> 01:56.028
You have on writer's face.

01:56.072 --> 01:57.615
What... No, I had writer's face before.

01:57.639 --> 01:59.119
This is public remarks face.

01:59.162 --> 02:00.250
Oh. Well, okay.

02:00.294 --> 02:02.470
Let's do this.Okay.

02:02.513 --> 02:04.167
Thank you.

02:04.211 --> 02:06.169
Okay.

02:16.223 --> 02:20.140
Ladies and gentlemen,
President Elizabeth McCord

02:20.183 --> 02:22.751
and First Gentleman
Dr. Henry McCord.

02:30.106 --> 02:32.761
Madam Secretary,
it's a pleasure to see you.

02:32.804 --> 02:35.633
And you, too, Madam President.

02:35.677 --> 02:40.203
Is Minister Chen playing nice
on the Taiwanese negotiations?

02:40.247 --> 02:42.684
Oh, I've got his number.
I think he misses you.

02:42.727 --> 02:45.121
Excuse me.

02:45.165 --> 02:47.079
Hi, you. MIKE:
Senators Windbag

02:47.123 --> 02:48.733
and Expediency are
here as expected.

02:48.777 --> 02:50.518
Good to see you.

02:50.561 --> 02:53.173
Good evening, Mike. Not if we can't get
your wildly unrealistic,

02:53.216 --> 02:55.175
giving-me-palpitations
legislative meatball

02:55.218 --> 02:56.456
over the finish line. Thank you.

02:56.480 --> 02:58.221
You have votes to whip,
lady. I mean, Madam.

02:58.265 --> 03:00.136
President. I was sort of hoping

03:00.180 --> 03:01.833
to take the night off.

03:01.877 --> 03:03.922
So, Wagner likes
to feel important.

03:03.966 --> 03:06.074
So just act like you're there
seeking his brilliant counsel

03:06.098 --> 03:07.665
and actually give a crap

03:07.709 --> 03:09.101
about his spectacular
blowhardery.

03:09.145 --> 03:12.192
That and he likes to brag
about bringing home the bacon

03:12.235 --> 03:13.671
to his constituents.

03:13.715 --> 03:17.066
Langston is an idealist
but responds to power,

03:17.109 --> 03:18.937
so just pummel her.

03:18.981 --> 03:22.245
Isn't it a bit unseemly
for the president to pummel?

03:22.289 --> 03:26.249
Failure is unseemlier, and your
hundredth day in office looms.

03:29.252 --> 03:33.082
Now, see, that's something that
we can all reach consensus on.

03:33.125 --> 03:34.953
We ought to
chocolate-cover every bill

03:34.997 --> 03:37.956
that comes to the
floor, Madam President.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.350
Thanks for coming out tonight,
Senator Wagner.

03:40.394 --> 03:43.919
Any chance to hear that
scholarly husband of yours talk.

03:43.962 --> 03:46.313
Well, that's nice to hear.

03:46.356 --> 03:49.881
Be even nicer to hear if I had
your support for the ESI bill.

03:49.925 --> 03:53.581
I support
the infrastructure piece,

03:53.624 --> 03:56.714
but some of my colleagues and I
have concerns

03:56.758 --> 03:59.848
about the education handouts.

04:00.936 --> 04:04.896
Well, we can't have
next-gen infrastructure

04:04.940 --> 04:08.596
without innovations in science,
and we can't lead in science

04:08.639 --> 04:09.919
without investing
in education...

04:09.945 --> 04:12.817
The hip bone's connected
to the thigh bone.

04:12.861 --> 04:14.839
I've heard your pitch, ma'am,
but the people of Alabama

04:14.863 --> 04:16.952
don't care about
the body politic.

04:16.995 --> 04:19.998
They care about
runaway spending.

04:20.041 --> 04:21.738
Do you think

04:21.783 --> 04:25.743
that those concerns
might be allayed if we make sure

04:25.787 --> 04:27.919
contracts for rebuilding
Alabama's schools

04:27.963 --> 04:31.793
only go to local
construction companies?

04:33.360 --> 04:38.278
That might be just the chocolate
fix they need, Madam President.

04:40.280 --> 04:42.107
Before you all knew him

04:42.151 --> 04:45.850
as the First Gentleman
of the United States,

04:45.894 --> 04:48.940
he was known in many circles
for other things.

04:48.984 --> 04:52.857
Fighter pilot, religious
scholar, acclaimed author,

04:52.901 --> 04:54.903
White House advisor.

04:54.946 --> 04:56.426
Clearly, he did
the best he could

04:56.470 --> 04:58.254
with the limited talents he had.

04:59.951 --> 05:02.954
Please welcome Dr. Henry McCord.

05:06.480 --> 05:09.178
Thank you, Patricia.
Thank you very much.

05:09.221 --> 05:12.790
Well, it's true, I've had
a blessed and weird life

05:12.834 --> 05:14.966
and I've pursued
some challenging paths.

05:15.010 --> 05:17.795
But what you probably don't know
is that I could never have been

05:17.839 --> 05:21.843
any of those things
without poetry.

05:21.886 --> 05:24.367
I mean, here I was,
this goofy, working-class kid

05:24.411 --> 05:28.806
from Pittsburgh without a single
interesting thought in my mind.

05:28.850 --> 05:32.070
And then, in high school, I had
this great teacher, Mr. Eastman,

05:32.114 --> 05:36.945
who made me read Gerard Manley
Hopkins and Emily Dickinson

05:36.988 --> 05:40.949
and Langston Hughes
and Blaise Pascal.

05:40.992 --> 05:45.083
These were theologians,
philosophers, innovators

05:45.127 --> 05:46.476
and artists.

05:46.520 --> 05:50.959
And suddenly,
my mind caught fire.

05:51.002 --> 05:55.006
I... the way they used words
just lit up my imagination

05:55.050 --> 05:59.968
and expanded my concept
of the divine.

06:00.011 --> 06:03.841
They ignited all my passions
and put them in one place.

06:04.886 --> 06:07.105
In his poem "High Flight,"

06:07.149 --> 06:10.500
John Gillespie Magee Jr. wrote,

06:10.544 --> 06:14.374
"Oh, I have slipped
the surly bonds of earth,

06:14.417 --> 06:17.855
And danced the skies
on laughter-silvered wings."

06:17.899 --> 06:20.858
When I read that passage,
I instantly knew two things:

06:20.902 --> 06:24.993
I wanted to study theology
and I wanted to fly.

06:26.168 --> 06:29.301
Artists have inspired me
to do everything

06:29.345 --> 06:32.043
that's meaningful in my life.

06:32.087 --> 06:34.437
I may have even leaned on
a little Keats and Shakespeare

06:34.481 --> 06:36.439
when I was wooing
my beautiful wife.

06:40.182 --> 06:42.358
There is nothing that drives

06:42.402 --> 06:46.014
our world-leading economy
like creativity,

06:46.057 --> 06:50.845
and there is nothing that drives
creativity like the arts.

06:50.888 --> 06:55.850
It is vital that we foster them
and invest in them.

06:55.893 --> 06:57.504
Thank you very much.

07:00.942 --> 07:02.509
Don't tell people this, but...

07:02.552 --> 07:05.033
Thomas Aquinas walks
into a bar...

07:05.076 --> 07:08.558
I'm so sorry to pull rank, but
the first gentleman is needed

07:08.602 --> 07:10.473
for an emergency
dancing situation,

07:10.517 --> 07:11.909
and it can't be helped.Sorry.

07:11.953 --> 07:14.216
Can't say no to the chief.

07:14.259 --> 07:17.306
♪

07:17.349 --> 07:19.351
Well, hello.Hello.

07:21.136 --> 07:24.444
We haven't danced like this
since the inaugural ball.

07:24.487 --> 07:26.576
We haven't danced at
all since then.

07:26.620 --> 07:28.926
Well, there was
that midnight Macarena moment.

07:28.970 --> 07:31.276
Okay, that was fun.

07:35.063 --> 07:39.284
You know, sometimes I just can't
believe this is all real.

07:39.328 --> 07:40.982
Right?

07:41.025 --> 07:42.940
The only way I know
this isn't a dream

07:42.984 --> 07:45.073
is because I can
still work my phone.

07:45.116 --> 07:46.204
What?

07:46.248 --> 07:50.339
You can't work technology
in your dream.

07:50.382 --> 07:52.123
You're crazy. Yes, you can.No. You can't.

07:52.167 --> 07:53.821
I can. Yes, I can. No, you can't.

07:53.864 --> 07:55.257
It's scientifically proven.

07:55.300 --> 07:57.955
Oh, yeah? What... who
are the scientists... Yeah.

07:57.999 --> 07:59.348
That did this experiment?

07:59.391 --> 08:01.306
Well, I'm going to get
somebody on it.

08:06.529 --> 08:09.358
I love you, Henry McCord.

08:09.401 --> 08:11.969
I love you, Madam President.

08:12.013 --> 08:14.015
♪

08:19.542 --> 08:21.501
You can't beat this commute.

08:21.544 --> 08:22.980
No.From now on,

08:23.024 --> 08:24.939
let's only have jobs
that are in our house.

08:24.982 --> 08:26.331
I agree.

08:26.375 --> 08:28.072
Well, I go left here.

08:28.116 --> 08:29.987
Okay, have a good day.
Keep an open mind.

08:30.031 --> 08:31.423
About what?

08:32.207 --> 08:34.339
Anything that comes up.

08:34.383 --> 08:35.688
Elizabeth...

08:35.732 --> 08:37.318
It's just all-around
solid advice. I love you.

08:37.342 --> 08:39.431
Uh... Morning,
Dr. McCord.

08:39.475 --> 08:42.019
Good morning, Evan. Last night's speech
already paying dividends.

08:42.043 --> 08:44.195
Well, let's hear it. Two more senators
and five House members

08:44.219 --> 08:46.090
signed on to your increased
NEA-funding push.

08:46.134 --> 08:47.614
My kind of dividends.

08:47.657 --> 08:49.877
And you're confirmed for
Colbertthis afternoon.

08:49.920 --> 08:52.183
Cool. And terrifying. Flying
out of Andrews at 1300.

08:52.227 --> 08:54.359
Um, and Jason's definitely
coming with, right?

08:54.403 --> 08:57.058
I'll make sure he's got a seat.
And you have a visitor.

08:59.277 --> 09:00.888
Roxanne.

09:00.931 --> 09:02.629
This is a surprise. Really, Dr. McCord?

09:02.672 --> 09:04.892
I convinced the
commander in chief.

09:06.589 --> 09:08.069
Meet your new wardrobe.

09:10.114 --> 09:11.202
Oh, hey.

09:11.246 --> 09:12.595
Good timing.

09:12.639 --> 09:14.902
I know I haven't brought this up
lately, or today,

09:14.945 --> 09:17.513
but this is day 98, which
means only two more days

09:17.557 --> 09:19.056
until I can quit. I know. I know, Mike.

09:19.080 --> 09:20.168
Do you, though?

09:20.211 --> 09:22.387
Yes. I-I have
your shortlist on my desk.

09:22.431 --> 09:23.563
Actually, here it is again,

09:23.606 --> 09:24.714
because I fished it
out from the pile

09:24.738 --> 09:25.932
and gingerly blew
the dust off of it.

09:25.956 --> 09:28.480
You haven't brought
any of those people in.

09:28.524 --> 09:31.222
I will. Yes, you will, because
the leader of the free world

09:31.266 --> 09:32.920
would not go back on her word.

09:32.963 --> 09:34.922
No, she wouldn't.

09:34.965 --> 09:37.577
Look, I don't want the
job Jay Whitman rejected.

09:37.620 --> 09:39.709
I want the job you promised me:

09:39.753 --> 09:41.232
counselor to the president.

09:41.276 --> 09:43.234
Behind the scenes,
under the radar.

09:43.278 --> 09:46.063
Cracking heads
and crushing enemies.

09:46.107 --> 09:49.414
But you're so good
at being my chief of staff.

09:49.458 --> 09:52.592
Acting chief of staff,
and of course I'm amazing at it.

09:52.635 --> 09:54.245
But I hate it.

09:54.289 --> 09:56.030
It's all relationships
and people.

09:56.073 --> 09:58.380
So many people... in person.

09:59.424 --> 10:01.209
Well, I'm gonna need
some more time.

10:01.252 --> 10:03.080
No. No, that was not the deal.

10:03.124 --> 10:06.083
I agreed to filling in
for the first 100 days.

10:06.127 --> 10:07.519
We shook on it.

10:07.563 --> 10:10.261
Don't punish me because Jay
had a mental breakdown.

10:10.305 --> 10:11.567
It wasn't a breakdown.

10:11.611 --> 10:13.221
Total breakdown. It was love.

10:13.264 --> 10:15.547
What's the difference? The kid
walked out on his dream job.

10:15.571 --> 10:16.703
For what? A chess player?

10:16.746 --> 10:19.009
To be happy? From Holland?

10:19.053 --> 10:20.663
That's sexy. To start a family?

10:20.707 --> 10:23.144
To not end up alone?

10:23.187 --> 10:24.624
Oh, what's that?

10:24.667 --> 10:27.104
Clearly,
things you don't care about.

10:27.148 --> 10:29.126
Yeah, and I cannot care about those
things... Exactly why you are perfect

10:29.150 --> 10:31.030
for this job....when I have the job
that I want.

10:31.065 --> 10:34.024
Okay, I hear you.

10:34.068 --> 10:35.635
Until then? Whip count is 58

10:35.678 --> 10:37.569
after you secured Langston
and Wagner last night.

10:37.593 --> 10:39.987
Well, that's great. It's great-adjacent.

10:40.030 --> 10:42.139
We're still two votes shy
of a filibuster-proof majority,

10:42.163 --> 10:44.358
so start thinking about which kid you're
willing to sacrifice. Good morning, ma'am.

10:44.382 --> 10:45.533
Good morning. Lemon poppyseed.

10:45.557 --> 10:47.472
What did you call me?

10:47.516 --> 10:50.316
You really need to calm down. And see?
He's back to being an assistant.

10:50.345 --> 10:52.652
Uh, ROTUS. Receptionist
of the United States.

10:52.695 --> 10:54.479
That's worse. That's a promotion.

10:54.523 --> 10:55.872
That's how she gets you.

10:55.916 --> 10:57.676
Okay. Ma'am, Ephraim Ware
and FBI Director Banks

10:57.700 --> 10:59.156
are in your office.
They say it's urgent.

10:59.180 --> 11:00.442
More urgent than passing

11:00.485 --> 11:01.443
the most ambitious
legislative tour de force

11:01.486 --> 11:02.836
of the century? Morning.

11:02.879 --> 11:05.360
New intel on the Knights
of Western Freedom or...?

11:05.403 --> 11:08.015
No, ma'am. It's Iran.

11:08.058 --> 11:09.581
That's never good.

11:09.625 --> 11:10.985
Madam President,
yesterday morning,

11:11.018 --> 11:13.585
I received a call
from my counterpart in Mossad.

11:13.629 --> 11:15.762
During an Israeli
counterintelligence operation,

11:15.805 --> 11:18.373
agents came across
court documents

11:18.416 --> 11:21.332
from Senator Beauregard Miller's
divorce on a VAJA server.

11:21.376 --> 11:23.813
Which documents? Same ones

11:23.857 --> 11:25.095
about Miller cheating
on his wife,

11:25.119 --> 11:26.618
fathering a child with
one of his staffers

11:26.642 --> 11:29.036
that were leaked to a
reporter during the campaign.

11:29.079 --> 11:31.603
And Mossad thinks
the Iranians hacked them?

11:31.647 --> 11:33.562
Yes, ma'am, and the
Bureau's own metadata

11:33.605 --> 11:37.087
and friends at code analysis
confirm Iranian origin.

11:37.131 --> 11:38.499
- Let's not panic.
- Valerie Guillen,

11:38.523 --> 11:39.631
from The Chronicle,
she broke the story.

11:39.655 --> 11:40.676
What does she have to say?

11:40.700 --> 11:41.657
She's not giving up her source.

11:41.701 --> 11:42.876
But she denies

11:42.919 --> 11:44.157
receiving the documents
from the Iranians.

11:44.181 --> 11:45.202
She could have gotten them

11:45.226 --> 11:46.575
through a third party.

11:46.618 --> 11:48.359
If I may, ma'am.

11:48.403 --> 11:52.755
Our working theory is that Iran
targeted Miller's campaign

11:52.799 --> 11:56.585
because of his aggressively
anti-Iranian positions,

11:56.628 --> 11:59.762
and because he was
a harsh critic

11:59.806 --> 12:03.374
of your role in
landing the Iran peace deal.

12:03.418 --> 12:04.724
Okay, now we can panic.

12:06.421 --> 12:10.120
I want to know exactly
what happened, and who

12:10.164 --> 12:12.383
in the Iranian leadership
was responsible. Thank you.

12:12.427 --> 12:15.082
We're on it. You bet, Madam President.

12:16.170 --> 12:18.825
Gather the NSC.

12:18.868 --> 12:21.088
I want CYBERCOM

12:21.131 --> 12:24.091
to draw up severe
countermeasures.

12:25.788 --> 12:28.399
If it gets out that Iran
tried to tank

12:28.443 --> 12:30.445
your biggest rival's campaign
in order to help you,

12:30.488 --> 12:34.101
it could taint the
legitimacy of your election.

12:34.144 --> 12:38.322
This is much bigger
than my election.

12:38.366 --> 12:41.238
Our democracy was attacked
by a foreign power,

12:41.282 --> 12:43.588
and we have to defend it
at all costs.

12:49.769 --> 12:51.771
♪

13:03.521 --> 13:06.829
Really, the... the AC is up

13:06.873 --> 13:07.917
full throttle?

13:07.961 --> 13:09.571
Afraid so, ma'am.

13:09.614 --> 13:11.573
Whew.

13:11.616 --> 13:14.837
Oh, my God.
What is that smell?

13:14.881 --> 13:17.274
Is somebody sick? No, no, no, I think

13:17.318 --> 13:20.277
somebody left some, uh,
egg salad on the, uh...

13:20.321 --> 13:21.844
Under the seats last night.

13:21.888 --> 13:23.604
They're working on it.
I'm gonna, I'm gonna go check.

13:23.628 --> 13:25.456
Here's some good news, ma'am.

13:25.500 --> 13:27.328
I just heard that Sprinkles
is going

13:27.371 --> 13:29.156
to name a cupcake after you.

13:29.199 --> 13:31.854
Polls are that bad?

13:31.898 --> 13:33.290
Ma'am?

13:35.336 --> 13:38.818
If the cupcake thing
is the good news...

13:38.861 --> 13:41.298
No, actually, Hubbard dropped
a point or two today.

13:41.342 --> 13:42.473
You held.

13:42.517 --> 13:44.911
So I'm only four points
behind Hubbard?

13:44.954 --> 13:46.390
Yes. And
Miller's spread

13:46.434 --> 13:48.697
is all over the place,
depending on the poll.

13:48.740 --> 13:50.655
Give me Quinnipiac.

13:50.699 --> 13:52.440
Fourteen.

13:52.483 --> 13:55.356
Geez!

13:55.399 --> 13:58.315
He got that big of a bump
from The View?

13:58.359 --> 14:00.119
Well, he made salmon tacos.
They look good. MIKE: Hello?

14:00.143 --> 14:05.670
Welcome to the best day
of your lives so far.

14:05.714 --> 14:08.499
What is that smell...
It doesn't matter.

14:08.543 --> 14:09.805
It doesn't matter.

14:09.849 --> 14:11.502
I got a tip
from my Chronicleguy.

14:11.546 --> 14:13.504
Story breaks tomorrow.
Miller...

14:13.548 --> 14:15.419
cheated on his wife

14:15.463 --> 14:17.528
and secretly fathered a child
with one of his staffers.

